| `strategy-001-classicality-budget-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Three-phase derive-compute-adjudicate protocol for formula verification. Parallel Phase 1 is optimal. Mandate mission-critical explorations (don't leave experimental tests as optional). Best findings often emerge as side effects of stress-test fixes. Front-load computation. |
| `strategy-001-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Constraint-catalog methodology for hard unsolved problems. Ground-clearing strategies produce Tier 2-3 results but not Tier 1 novelty. Make synthesis/adversarial phases mandatory with minimum allocations. Force constructive work (building operators), not just testing known ones. Prescribe data scale (millions of zeros, not thousands). |
| `strategy-001-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Reproduce→Extend→Stress-Test for computational missions. Survey explorations at the start pay for themselves. Pre-loading verified formulas compounds across explorations. Adversarial review should come early, not just at end. "Computation mandatory" was the single most important rule. First strategies should prioritize breadth over depth. |
| `strategy-001-compton-unruh-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Adversarial Derivation Protocol for hypothesis-testing missions. Dimensional analysis as Phase 1 gatekeeper saves entire budgets. Adversarial tests must come early (slot 3-4), not late (slot 8). Pre-launch algebra checks prevent trivially-doomed explorations. Side-effects of failures produce the most interesting findings. One strategy can be sufficient for binary yes/no missions. |
| `strategy-001-yang-mills-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Probe-Attack-Synthesize for hard unsolved problems. First strategy = ground-clearing, second = constructive. Adversarial review must come early (slot 6-7), not at the end. Require math specificity in methodology. Quantitative negative results (AC bounds 57-69x vacuous) reach Tier 3; qualitative ones don't. Pre-load all prior findings into next strategy. |
| `strategy-002-classicality-budget-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Focused claim-deepening protocol after a survey strategy. All explorations mandatory (no optional). Second strategies should target specific gaps, not re-explore. Prescriptive literature search (specific papers + search terms) beats exploratory. Two-strategy arc (survey → deepen) may be default for formula-verification missions. |
| `strategy-001-amplituhedron-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Compute-first methodology for framework comparison missions. "Compute first" was wrong emphasis for structural/conceptual domains — surveys produced better results. Match methodology to domain type. Framework-comparison missions follow map→characterize→probe→synthesize arc. Novel claims from well-studied fields will be synthesis, not discovery. One strategy can suffice for clearly scoped questions. |
| `strategy-002-sed-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Parallel probes for frontier mapping. All three probes produced novel data (none wasted). Two-strategy arc (depth then breadth) is natural for computational missions. Physical constant verification must be a cross-phase rule. Adversarial review MUST find prior art or it hasn't done its job. Tunneling formula R²=0.9998 was the mission's strongest result — emerged from a "quick probe" design. |
| `strategy-002-riemann-hypothesis-learnings.md` | 2026-03-27 | Tournament methodology for constructive research. Tournament→Deep Dive→Mandatory Adversarial is the best three-phase arc for constructive missions. Adversarial review is the highest-ROI phase — it caught two false claims. Construction strategies produce better novelty than testing strategies. Prescribe specific null-hypothesis control experiments. Explorer death rate (4/9) is the #1 operational problem. |
